            <p>S. MORAIS&#44;<lb/>
                546 NORTH FIFTH ST.&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Philadelphia. December 13th 1888<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. S. M. Fleischman<lb/>
                My Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>In justice to myself and in obe&#45;<lb/>dience to a sense of duty&#44; I must answer your note<lb/> just received at some length.  It was due to you that<lb/> I should say what I knew to be the object of Mrs<lb/> Weiss&#39; request.  To conceal it would have been to do<lb/> violence to the rules that have guided me through life&#44;<lb/> and to act offensively towards one to whom was com&#45;<lb/>mitted the best interest of a Jewish Institution.<lb/></p>
            <p>But you will permit me to say that as a teacher<lb/> of our people&#44; who will never limit himself in the<lb/> discharge of what he deems his religious <del>duties</del> obligations&#44; I<lb/> could not refuse to comply with Mrs W&#39;s wish.<lb/>  Naturally&#44; you were to be consulted&#44; before her<lb/> boy should come to me for instruction in an<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>observance which she evidently values&#44; <del>and which I<lb/> have always followed</del>&#44; but to withhold my services<lb/> when asked in sincerity of feelings&#44; I dared not.<lb/>  It would be arrogant on my part to discuss<lb/> the importance of the ceremonial injustice of the<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; Phylactories in a letter simply &#91;&#63;&#93; to place myself<lb/> in a right light.  I may regret that we differ&#44;<lb/> the more to for reasons which your clear under&#45;<lb/>&#45;standing will interpret at once&#44; but as I dis&#45;<lb/>claim any right to act in the capacity of a<lb/> public mentor&#44; I shall say nothing further.<lb/>  With kind regards&#44; and <del>sincere</del> good wishes for<lb/> the prosperity of the Home&#44; I remain<lb/> Yours truly<lb/> S. Morais<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
